      {"id": "Ce0ddFqDIekcTc0W", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>Launch</p>", "<p>If we let C represent the cost of a pizza and N represent the number of pizzas,</p>"]}},
      [
        {
          "id": "aOBBfjAILB8J9wsO",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p>Royal Pizza</p>",
              "<p>Proportion    OR    Linear</p>",
              "<p>Equation                      Equation</p>",
              "<p>C/N  = 13/1             OR      C = 13N</p>",
              "<p>With the proportional situation, both equations are equivalent. You can multiply one variable by a constant number to get the value of the other variable.</p>",
              "<p></p>"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "VLndSuMeVRsGUjqc",
          "content": {
            "type": "Text",
            "format": "html",
            "text": [
              "<p>Howdyâ€™s Pizza</p>",
              "<p></p>",
              "<p>Linear Equation</p>",
              "<p></p>",
              "<p>C = 11N + 30</p>",
              "<p></p>",
              "<p>You cannot write C = 11N + 30 as a proportion. The add-on changes the unit rate with each N. So there is no constant of proportionality. You cannot multiply one variable by a constant number to get the value of the other variable.</p>"
            ]
          }
        }
      ],
      {"id": "zUaaoxdPbicBpQ-C", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>Note:  The unit rate,  (5 pizzas)/$65=  (5/65)/$1  or 5/65 pizza for $1, exists but it might not be as useful depending on the situation.</p>"]}},
      {
